<br>
The skirmishes, however, had left the Iksar drained both physically and mentally.  It was time to take some time to recuperate.  His regenerative powers, enhanced by countless seasons of battle began to do its work.  His older, scarred scales began to drop off, falling around him, to be replaced by brand new ones.  Within an hour’s time, the process had completed.  His entire skin had been cast away, and his new scales, so new they still shone with apparent wetness, were visible.  The only mark that lasted from one shedding to another was the sigil of the Dragon of Hate, branded upon his right bicep by Lord Cazic Thule as a constant reminder to him of his failure to the Lord of Fear.<br>
<br>
In the shadows, however, something watched the Iksar, carefully calculating when it would make its move.  Already the Prophet of the Harvest had been…disposed of.  The Dread Overlords were being hunted down as well.  With them out of the way, along with the meddling Ambassador, the plans could continue.  There were rumors the Iksar never slept anymore.  No matter.  The monk wasn’t the only thing here that had patience.  The patience of the Eternals would be of use.  The thing’s fangs dripped in anticipation of the hunt.<br>
<br>
This had been a long time in coming.<br>
